# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] The **Burrows–Wheeler transform** (**BWT**) rearranges a character string into runs of similar characters, in a manner that can be reversed to recover the original string.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] Since compression techniques such as move-to-front transform and run-length encoding are more effective when such runs are present, the BWT can be used as a preparatory step to improve the efficiency of a compression algorithm, and is used this way in software such as bzip2.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] The algorithm can be implemented efficiently using a suffix array thus reaching linear time complexity.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] It was invented by David Wheeler in 1983, and later published by him and Michael Burrows in 1994.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] Their paper included a compression algorithm, called the **Block-sorting Lossless Data Compression Algorithm** or **BSLDCA**, that compresses data by using the BWT followed by move-to-front coding and Huffman coding or arithmetic coding.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] The transform is done by constructing a matrix (known as the Burrows–Wheeler matrix) whose rows are the circular shifts of the input text, sorted in lexicographic order, then taking the final column of that matrix.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] The output of the encoding phase is the last column `L = BNN^AA$A` after step 3, and the index (0-based) `I` of the row containing the original string `S`, in this case `I = 6`.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] It is not necessary to use both `$` and `^`, but at least one must be used, else we cannot invert the transform, since all circular permutations of a string have the same Burrows–Wheeler transform.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] The following pseudocode gives a simple (though inefficient) way to calculate the BWT and its inverse.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] It assumes that the input string `s` contains a special character "EOF", which is the last character and occurs nowhere else in the text.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] If the original string had several substrings that occurred often, then the BWT-transformed string will have several places where a single character is repeated many times in a row, creating more-easily-compressible data.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] Similarly, rotations beginning with "e " are grouped together, but "e " is often preceded by "h", so we see the output above contains a run of five consecutive "h" characters.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] Thus it can be seen that the success of this transform depends upon one value having a high probability of occurring before a sequence, so that in general it needs fairly long samples (a few kilobytes at least) of appropriate data (such as text).
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] The remarkable thing about the BWT is not that it generates a more easily encoded output—an ordinary sort would do that—but that it does this *reversibly*, allowing the original document to be re-generated from the last column data.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] Take the final table in the BWT algorithm, and erase all but the last column.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] Given only this information, you can easily reconstruct the first column.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] The last column tells you all the characters in the text, so just sort these characters alphabetically to get the first column.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] Then, the last and first columns (of each row) together give you all *pairs* of successive characters in the document, where pairs are taken cyclically so that the last and first character form a pair.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] Sorting the list of pairs gives the first *and second* columns.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] To obtain the third column, the last column is again prepended to the table, and the rows are sorted lexicographically.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] Continuing in this manner, you can reconstruct the entire list.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] Then, the row with the "end of file" character at the end is the original text.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] A number of optimizations can make these algorithms run more efficiently without changing the output.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] There is no need to represent the table in either the encoder or decoder.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] In the encoder, each row of the table can be represented by a single pointer into the strings, and the sort performed using the indices.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] In the decoder, there is also no need to store the table, and the decoded string can be generated one character at a time from left to right.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] Comparative sorting can even be avoided in favor of linear sorting, with performance proportional to the alphabet size and string length.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] A "character" in the algorithm can be a byte, or a bit, or any other convenient size.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] One may also make the observation that mathematically, the encoded string can be computed as a simple modification of the suffix array, and suffix arrays can be computed with linear time and memory.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] There is no need to have an actual 'EOF' character.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] Instead, a pointer can be used that remembers where in a string the 'EOF' would be if it existed.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] In this approach, the output of the BWT must include both the transformed string, and the final value of the pointer.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] The inverse transform then shrinks it back down to the original size: it is given a string and a pointer, and returns just a string.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] A complete description of the algorithms can be found in Burrows and Wheeler's paper, or in a number of online sources.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] The algorithms vary somewhat by whether EOF is used, and in which direction the sorting was done.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] In fact, the original formulation did not use an EOF marker.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] Since any rotation of the input string will lead to the same transformed string, the BWT cannot be inverted without adding an EOF marker to the end of the input or doing something equivalent, making it possible to distinguish the input string from all its rotations.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] Increasing the size of the alphabet (by appending the EOF character) makes later compression steps awkward.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] There is a bijective version of the transform, by which the transformed string uniquely identifies the original, and the two have the same length and contain exactly the same characters, just in a different order.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] The bijective transform is computed by factoring the input into a non-increasing sequence of Lyndon words; such a factorization exists and is unique by the Chen–Fox–Lyndon theorem, and may be found in linear time and constant space.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] The algorithm sorts the rotations of all the words; as in the Burrows–Wheeler transform, this produces a sorted sequence of *n* strings.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] The transformed string is then obtained by picking the final character of each string in this sorted list.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] The one important caveat here is that strings of different lengths are not ordered in the usual way; the two strings are repeated forever, and the infinite repeats are sorted.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] For example, "ORO" precedes "OR" because "OROORO..." precedes "OROROR...".
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] For example, the text "^BANANA$" is transformed into "ANNBAA^$" through these steps (the red $ character indicates the EOF pointer) in the original string.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] The EOF character is unneeded in the bijective transform, so it is dropped during the transform and re-added to its proper place in the file.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] The string is broken into Lyndon words so the words in the sequence are decreasing using the comparison method above.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] (Note that we're sorting '^' as succeeding other characters.) "^BANANA" becomes (^) (B) (AN) (AN) (A).
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] Up until the last step, the process is identical to the inverse Burrows–Wheeler process, but here it will not necessarily give rotations of a single sequence; it instead gives rotations of Lyndon words (which will start to repeat as the process is continued).
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] Here, we can see (repetitions of) four distinct Lyndon words: (A), (AN) (twice), (B), and (^).
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] (NANA... doesn't represent a distinct word, as it is a cycle of ANAN....) At this point, these words are sorted into reverse order: (^), (B), (AN), (AN), (A).
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] The whole string is now a Lyndon word, and running it through the bijective process will therefore result in a transformed result that, when inverted, gives back the Lyndon word, with no need for reassembling at the end.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] The bijective transform includes eight runs of identical characters.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] In total, 18 characters are used in these runs.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] When a text is edited, its Burrows–Wheeler transform will change.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] This Python implementation sacrifices speed for simplicity: the program is short, but takes more than the linear time that would be desired in a practical implementation.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] It essentially does what the pseudocode section does.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] The inverse transform repeatedly inserts `r` as the left column of the table and sorts the table.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] After the whole table is built, it returns the row that ends with ETX, minus the STX and ETX.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] Following implementation notes from Manzini, it is equivalent to use a simple null character suffix instead.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] The sorting should be done in colexicographic order (string read right-to-left), i.e.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] (The above control codes actually fail to satisfy EOF being the last character; the two codes are actually the *first*.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] As a lossless compression algorithm the Burrows–Wheeler transform offers the important quality that its encoding is reversible and hence the original data may be recovered from the resulting compression.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] The lossless quality of Burrows algorithm has provided for different algorithms with different purposes in mind.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] To name a few, Burrows–Wheeler transform is used in algorithms for sequence alignment, image compression, data compression, etc.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] The following is a compilation of some uses given to the Burrows–Wheeler Transform.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] The advent of next-generation sequencing (NGS) techniques at the end of the 2000s decade has led to another application of the Burrows–Wheeler transformation.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] In NGS, DNA is fragmented into small pieces, of which the first few bases are sequenced, yielding several millions of "reads", each 30 to 500 base pairs ("DNA characters") long.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] In many experiments, e.g., in ChIP-Seq, the task is now to align these reads to a reference genome, i.e., to the known, nearly complete sequence of the organism in question (which may be up to several billion base pairs long).
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] A number of alignment programs, specialized for this task, were published, which initially relied on hashing (e.g., Eland, SOAP, or Maq).
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] In an effort to reduce the memory requirement for sequence alignment, several alignment programs were developed (Bowtie, BWA, and SOAP2) that use the Burrows–Wheeler transform.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] The Burrows–Wheeler transformation has proved to be fundamental for image compression applications.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] For example, Showed a compression pipeline based on the application of the Burrows–Wheeler transformation followed by inversion, run-length, and arithmetic encoders.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] The pipeline developed in this case is known as Burrows–Wheeler transform with an inversion encoder (BWIC).
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] The results shown by BWIC are shown to outperform the compression performance of well-known and widely used algorithms like Lossless JPEG and JPEG 2000.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] BWIC is shown to outperform those in terms of final compression size of radiography medical images on the order of 5.1% and 4.1% respectively.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] The improvements are achieved by combining BWIC and a pre-BWIC scan of the image in a vertical snake order fashion.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] More recently, additional works have shown the implementation of the Burrows–Wheeler Transform in conjunction with the known move-to-front transform (MTF) achieve near lossless compression of images.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] Cox et al. presented a genomic compression scheme that uses BWT as the algorithm applied during the first stage of compression of several genomic datasets including the human genomic information.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] Their work proposed that BWT compression could be enhanced by including a second stage compression mechanism called same-as-previous encoding ("SAP"), which makes use of the fact that suffixes of two or more prefix letters could be equal.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] With the compression mechanism BWT-SAP, Cox et al. showed that in the genomic database ERA015743, 135.5 GB in size, the compression scheme BWT-SAP compresses the ERA015743 dataset by around 94%, to 8.2 GB.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] BWT has also been proved to be useful on sequence prediction which is a common area of study in machine learning and natural-language processing.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] In particular, Ktistakis et al. proposed a sequence prediction scheme called SuBSeq that exploits the lossless compression of data of the Burrows–Wheeler transform.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] SuBSeq exploits BWT by extracting the FM-index and then performing a series of operations called backwardSearch, forwardSearch, neighbourExpansion, and getConsequents in order to search for predictions given a suffix.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] The predictions are then classified based on a weight and put into an array from which the element with the highest weight is given as the prediction from the SuBSeq algorithm.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/burrows-wheeler-transform] SuBSeq has been shown to outperform state of the art algorithms for sequence prediction both in terms of training time and accuracy.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] bzip2 is not a file archiver and thus relies on separate external utilities such as `tar` for tasks such as handling multiple files, and other tools for encryption, and archive splitting.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] bzip2 was initially released in 1996 (originally named **bzip**) by Julian Seward.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] It compresses most files more effectively than older LZW and Deflate compression algorithms but is slower. bzip2 is particularly efficient for text data, and decompression is relatively fast.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] The move-to-front transform and Huffman coding are then applied.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] The compression performance is asymmetric, with decompression being faster than compression.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] The algorithm has gone through multiple maintainers since its initial release, with Micah Snyder being the maintainer since June 2021.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] There have been some modifications to the algorithm, such as pbzip2 and lbzip2, which use multi-threading to improve compression speed on multi-CPU and multi-core computers.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] bzip2 is suitable for use in big data applications with cluster computing frameworks like Hadoop and Apache Spark, as a compressed block can be decompressed without having to process earlier blocks.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] The bundled *bzip2recover* utility tries recovering readable parts of damaged bzip2 data.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] It works by searching for individual blocks and dumping them into separate files.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] Seward made the first public release of bzip, version 0.15, in July 1996.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] Due to software patent issues, bzip2 version 0.1 was released in August 1997, with Huffman coding replacing the arithmetic coding used by bzip.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] The format in which bzip2 is created was not compatible with bzip and any efforts to make both the programs compatibility were not met because of the patent issues. bzip is no longer available and is replaced by bzip2.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] The compressor's stability and popularity grew over the next several years, and Seward released version 1.0 in late 2000.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] Following a nine-year hiatus of updates for the project since 2010, on 4 June 2019 Federico Mena accepted maintainership of the bzip2 project.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] Since June 2021, the maintainer is Micah Snyder.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] Burrows–Wheeler transform (BWT), or block sorting.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] Run-length encoding (RLE) of MTF result.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] Selection between multiple Huffman tables.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] Unary base-1 encoding of Huffman table selection.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] Delta encoding (Δ) of Huffman-code bit lengths.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] Sparse bit array showing which symbols are used.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] Any sequence of 4 to 255 consecutive duplicate symbols is replaced by the first 4 symbols and a repeat length between 0 and 251.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] Thus the sequence `AAAAAAABBBBCCCD` is replaced with `AAAA\3BBBB\0CCCD`, where `\3` and `\0` represent byte values 3 and 0 respectively.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] Runs of symbols are always transformed after 4 consecutive symbols, even if the run-length is set to zero, to keep the transformation reversible.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] In the worst case, it can cause an expansion of 1.25, and in the best case, a reduction to <0.02.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] While the specification theoretically allows for runs of length 256–259 to be encoded, the reference encoder will not produce such output.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] The author of bzip2 has stated that the RLE step was a historical mistake and was only intended to protect the original BWT implementation from pathological cases.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] The Burrows–Wheeler transform is the reversible block-sort that is at the core of bzip2.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] The block is entirely self-contained, with input and output buffers remaining of the same size—in bzip2, the operating limit for this stage is 900 kB.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] For the block-sort, a (notional) matrix is created, in which row *i* contains the whole of the buffer, rotated to start from the *i*-th symbol.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] Following rotation, the rows of the matrix are sorted into alphabetic (numerical) order.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] A 24-bit pointer is stored marking the *starting position* for when the block is untransformed.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] In practice, it is not necessary to construct the full matrix; rather, the sort is performed using pointers for each position in the buffer.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] The output buffer is the last column of the matrix; this contains the whole buffer, but reordered so that it is likely to contain large runs of identical symbols.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] The move-to-front transform again does not alter the size of the processed block.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] Each of the symbols in use in the document is placed in an array.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] When a symbol is processed, it is replaced by its location (index) in the array and that symbol is shuffled to the front of the array.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] The effect is that immediately recurring symbols are replaced by zero symbols (long runs of *any* arbitrary symbol thus become runs of zero symbols), while other symbols are remapped according to their local frequency.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] Much "natural" data contains identical symbols that recur within a limited range (text is a good example).
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] As the MTF transform assigns low values to symbols that reappear frequently, this results in a data stream containing many symbols in the low integer range, many of them being identical (different recurring input symbols can actually map to the same output symbol).
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] Such data can be very efficiently encoded by any legacy compression method.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] Long strings of zeros in the output of the move-to-front transform (which come from repeated symbols in the output of the BWT) are replaced by a sequence of two special codes, RUNA and RUNB, which represent the run-length as a binary number.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] Actual zeros are never encoded in the output; a lone zero becomes RUNA.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] The sequence `0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1` would be represented as `RUNA, RUNB, 1`; `RUNA, RUNB` represents the value 5 as described below.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] The run-length code is terminated by reaching another normal symbol.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] This RLE process is more flexible than the initial RLE step, as it is able to encode arbitrarily long integers (in practice, this is usually limited by the block size, so that this step does not encode a run of more than 900000 bytes).
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] The run-length is encoded in this fashion: assigning place values of 1 to the first bit, 2 to the second, 4 to the third, etc. in the sequence, multiply each place value in a RUNB spot by 2, and add all the resulting place values (for RUNA and RUNB values alike) together.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] This is similar to base-2 bijective numeration.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] Thus, the sequence `RUNA, RUNB` results in the value (1 + 2 × 2) = 5.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] This process replaces fixed-length symbols in the range 0–258 with variable-length codes based on the frequency of use.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] More frequently used codes end up shorter (2–3 bits), whilst rare codes can be allocated up to 20 bits.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] The codes are selected carefully so that no sequence of bits can be confused for a different code.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] The end-of-stream code is particularly interesting.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] If there are *n* different bytes (symbols) used in the uncompressed data, then the Huffman code will consist of two RLE codes (RUNA and RUNB), *n* − 1 symbol codes and one end-of-stream code.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] In the extreme case where only one symbol is used in the uncompressed data, there will be no symbol codes at all in the Huffman tree, and the entire block will consist of RUNA and RUNB (implicitly repeating the single byte) and an end-of-stream marker with value 2.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] 258: end of stream, finish processing (could be as low as 2).
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] Several identically sized Huffman tables can be used with a block if the gain from using them is greater than the cost of including the extra table.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] At least 2 and up to 6 tables can be present, with the most appropriate table being reselected before every 50 symbols processed.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] This has the advantage of having very responsive Huffman dynamics without having to continuously supply new tables, as would be required in DEFLATE.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] Run-length encoding in the previous step is designed to take care of codes that have an inverse probability of use higher than the shortest code Huffman code in use.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] If multiple Huffman tables are in use, the selection of each table (numbered 0 to 5) is done from a list by a zero-terminated bit run between 1 and 6 bits in length.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] The selection is into a MTF list of the tables.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] Using this feature results in a maximal expansion of around 1.015, but generally less.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] This expansion is likely to be greatly over-shadowed by the advantage of selecting more appropriate Huffman tables, and the common-case of continuing to use the same Huffman table is represented as a single bit.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] Rather than unary encoding, effectively this is an extreme form of a Huffman tree, where each code has half the probability of the previous code.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] Huffman-code bit lengths are required to reconstruct each of the used canonical Huffman tables.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] Each bit length is stored as an encoded difference against the previous-code bit length.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] A zero bit (0) means that the previous bit length should be duplicated for the current code, whilst a one bit (1) means that a further bit should be read and the bit length incremented or decremented based on that value.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] In the common case a single bit is used per symbol per table and the worst case—going from length 1 to length 20—would require approximately 37 bits.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] As a result of the earlier MTF encoding, code lengths would start at 2–3 bits long (very frequently used codes) and gradually increase, meaning that the delta format is fairly efficient, requiring around 300 bits (38 bytes) per full Huffman table.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] A bitmap is used to show which symbols are used inside the block and should be included in the Huffman trees.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] Binary data is likely to use all 256 symbols representable by a byte, whereas textual data may only use a small subset of available values, perhaps covering the ASCII range between 32 and 126.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] Storing 256 zero bits would be inefficient if they were mostly unused.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] A *sparse* method is used: the 256 symbols are divided up into 16 ranges, and only if symbols are used within that block is a 16-bit array included.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] The presence of each of these 16 ranges is indicated by an additional 16-bit bit array at the front.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] The total bitmap uses between 32 and 272 bits of storage (4–34 bytes).
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] For contrast, the DEFLATE algorithm would show the absence of symbols by encoding the symbols as having a zero bit length with run-length encoding and additional Huffman coding.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] No formal specification for bzip2 exists, although an informal specification has been reverse engineered from the reference implementation.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] As an overview, a `.bz2` stream consists of a 4-byte header, followed by zero or more compressed blocks, immediately followed by an end-of-stream marker containing a 32-bit CRC for the plaintext whole stream processed.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] The compressed blocks are bit-aligned and no padding occurs.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] Because of the first-stage RLE compression (see above), the maximum length of plaintext that a single 900 kB bzip2 block can contain is around 46 MB (45,899,236 bytes).
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] This can occur if the whole plaintext consists entirely of repeated values (the resulting `.bz2` file in this case is 46 bytes long).
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] An even smaller file of 40 bytes can be achieved by using an input containing entirely values of 251, an apparent compression ratio of 1147480.9:1.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] A compressed block in bzip2 can be decompressed without having to process earlier blocks.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] This means that bzip2 files can be decompressed in parallel, making it a good format for use in big data applications with cluster computing frameworks like Hadoop and Apache Spark.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] bzip2 compresses most files more effectively than the older LZW (.Z) and Deflate (.zip and .gz) compression algorithms, but is considerably slower.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] LZMA is generally more space-efficient than bzip2 at the expense of even slower compression speed, while having faster decompression.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] bzip2 compresses data in blocks of size between 100 and 900 kB and uses the Burrows–Wheeler transform to convert frequently-recurring character sequences into strings of identical letters.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] It then applies move-to-front transform and Huffman coding. bzip2's ancestor **bzip** used arithmetic coding instead of Huffman.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] The change was made because of a software patent restriction. bzip3, a modern compressor that shares common ancestry and set of algorithms with bzip2, switched back to arithmetic coding.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] bzip2 performance is asymmetric, as decompression is relatively fast.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] Motivated by the long time required for compression, a modified version was created in 2003 called pbzip2 that used multi-threading to encode the file in multiple chunks, giving almost linear speedup on multi-CPU and multi-core computers.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] As of May 2010, this functionality has not been incorporated into the main project.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] Like gzip, bzip2 is only a data compressor.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] It is not an archiver like tar or ZIP; the bzip2 file format does not support storing the contents of multiple files in a single compressed file, and the program itself has no facilities for multiple files, encryption or archive-splitting.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] In the UNIX tradition, archiving could be done by a separate program producing an archive which is then compressed with bzip2, and un-archiving could be done by bzip2 uncompressing the compressed archive file and a separate program decompressing it.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] Some archivers have built-in support for compression and decompression, so that it is not necessary to use the bzip2 program to compress or decompress the archive.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/bzip2] GnuPG also has built-in support for bzip2 compression and decompression.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] In computer science, an **FM-index** is a compressed full-text substring index based on the Burrows–Wheeler transform, with some similarities to the suffix array.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] It was created by Paolo Ferragina and Giovanni Manzini, who describe it as an opportunistic data structure as it allows compression of the input text while still permitting fast substring queries.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] The name stands for Full-text index in Minute space.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] It can be used to efficiently find the number of occurrences of a pattern within the compressed text, as well as locate the position of each occurrence.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] The query time, as well as the required storage space, has a sublinear complexity with respect to the size of the input data.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] The original authors have devised improvements to their original approach and dubbed it "FM-Index version 2".
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] A further improvement, the alphabet-friendly FM-index, combines the use of compression boosting and wavelet trees to significantly reduce the space usage for large alphabets.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] The FM-index has found use in, among other places, bioinformatics.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] Using an index is a common strategy to efficiently search a large body of text.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] When the text is larger than what reasonably fits within a computer's main memory, there is a need to compress not only the text but also the index.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] When the FM-index was introduced, there were several suggested solutions that were based on traditional compression methods and tried to solve the compressed matching problem.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] In contrast, the FM-index is a compressed self-index, which means that it compresses the data and indexes it at the same time.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] An FM-index is created by first taking the Burrows–Wheeler transform (BWT) of the input text.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] For example, the BWT of the string T = "abracadabra$" is "ard$rcaaaabb", and here it is represented by the matrix M where each row is a rotation of the text, and the rows have been sorted lexicographically.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] The transform corresponds to the concatenation of the characters from the last column (labeled L).
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] The BWT in itself allows for some compression with, for instance, move to front and Huffman encoding, but the transform has even more uses.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] The rows in the matrix are essentially the sorted suffixes of the text and the first column F of the matrix shares similarities with suffix arrays.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] How the suffix array relates to the BWT lies at the heart of the FM-index.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] It is possible to make a last-to-first column mapping LF(i) from an index i to an index j, such that F[j] = L[i], with the help of a table C[c] and a function Occ(c, k).
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] The last-to-first mapping can now be defined as LF(i) = C[L[i]] + Occ(L[i], i).
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] For instance, on row 9, L is a and the same a can be found on row 5 in the first column F, so LF(9) should be 5 and LF(9) = C[a] + Occ(a, 9) = 5.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] For any row i of the matrix, the character in the last column L[i] precedes the character in the first column F[i] also in T.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] Finally, if L[i] = T[k], then L[LF(i)] = T[k - 1], and using the equality it is possible to extract a string of T from L.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] The FM-index itself is a compression of the string L together with C and Occ in some form, as well as information that maps a selection of indices in L to positions in the original string T.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] The operation *count* takes a pattern P[1..p] and returns the number of occurrences of that pattern in the original text T.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] Since the rows of matrix M are sorted, and it contains every suffix of T, the occurrences of pattern P will be next to each other in a single continuous range.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] The operation iterates backwards over the pattern.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] For every character in the pattern, the range that has the character as a suffix is found.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] The new range is [C[r] + Occ(r, start-1) + 1 ..
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] 10 + 2] = [11..12], if start is the index of the beginning of the range and end is the end.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] This range over L is all the characters of T that have suffixes beginning with *ra*.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] The new range is [C[b] + Occ(b, start-1) + 1 ..
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] This range over L is all the characters that have a suffix that begins with *bra*.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] Now that the whole pattern has been processed, the count is the same as the size of the range: 8 - 7 + 1 = 2.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] If the range becomes empty or the range boundaries cross each other before the whole pattern has been looked up, the pattern does not occur in T.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] Because Occ(c, k) can be performed in constant time, count can complete in linear time in the length of the pattern: O(p) time.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] The operation *locate* takes as input an index of a character in L and returns its position i in T.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] To locate every occurrence of a pattern, first the range of character is found whose suffix is the pattern in the same way the *count* operation found the range.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] Then the position of every character in the range can be located.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] To map an index in L to one in T, a subset of the indices in L are associated with a position in T.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] If L[j] has a position associated with it, locate(j) is trivial.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] If it's not associated, the string is followed with LF(i) until an associated index is found.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] By associating a suitable number of indices, an upper bound can be found.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] *Locate* can be implemented to find *occ* occurrences of a pattern P[1..*p*] in a text T[1..*u*] in O(*p* + *occ* logε *u*) time with $O\left(H_{k}(T)+{{\log \log u} \over {\log ^{\epsilon }u}}\right)$ bits per input symbol for any *k* ≥ 0.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/fm-index] The FM-Index is available in multiple languages, including C++, Java and Rust.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] The **move-to-front (MTF) transform** is an encoding of data (typically a stream of bytes) designed to improve the performance of entropy encoding techniques of compression.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] When efficiently implemented, it is fast enough that its benefits usually justify including it as an extra step in data compression algorithm.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] This algorithm was first published by Boris Ryabko under the name of "book stack" in 1980.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] Subsequently, it was rediscovered by J.K.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] Bentley et al. in 1986, as attested in the explanatory note.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] The main idea is that each symbol in the data is replaced by its index in the stack of “recently used symbols”.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] For example, long sequences of identical symbols are replaced by as many zeroes, whereas when a symbol that has not been used in a long time appears, it is replaced with a large number.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] Thus at the end the data is transformed into a sequence of integers; if the data exhibits a lot of local correlations, then these integers tend to be small.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] Assume for simplicity that the symbols in the data are bytes.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] Each byte value is encoded by its index in a list of bytes, which changes over the course of the algorithm.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] The list is initially in order by byte value (0, 1, 2, 3, ..., 255).
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] Therefore, the first byte is always encoded by its own value.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] However, after encoding a byte, that value is moved to the front of the list before continuing to the next byte.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] An example will shed some light on how the transform works.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] Imagine instead of bytes, we are encoding values in a–z.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] By convention, the list is initially (abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz).
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] The first letter in the sequence is b, which appears at index 1 (the list is indexed from 0 to 25).
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] The b moves to the front of the list, producing (bacdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz).
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] The next letter is a, which now appears at index 1.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] and we move the letter a back to the top of the list.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] It is easy to see that the transform is reversible.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] Simply maintain the same list and decode by replacing each index in the encoded stream with the letter at that index in the list.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] Note the difference between this and the encoding method: The index in the list is used directly instead of looking up each value for its index.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] i.e. you start again with (abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz).
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] You take the "1" of the encoded block and look it up in the list, which results in "b".
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] Then move the "b" to front which results in (bacdef...).
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] Then take the next "1", look it up in the list, this results in "a", move the "a" to front ... etc.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] Details of implementation are important for performance, particularly for decoding.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] For encoding, no clear advantage is gained by using a linked list, so using an array to store the list is acceptable, with worst-case performance O(*n**k*), where *n* is the length of the data to be encoded and *k* is the number of values (generally a constant for a given implementation).
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] The typical performance is better because frequently used symbols are more likely to be at the front and will produce earlier hits.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] This is also the idea behind a Move-to-front self-organizing list.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] However, for decoding, we can use specialized data structures to greatly improve performance.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] This is a possible implementation of the move-to-front algorithm in Python.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] In this example we can see the MTF code taking advantage of the three repetitive `i`'s in the input word.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] The common dictionary here, however, is less than ideal since it is initialized with more commonly used ASCII printable characters put after little-used control codes, against the MTF code's design intent of keeping what's commonly used in the front.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] The MTF transform takes advantage of local correlation of frequencies to reduce the entropy of a message.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] Indeed, recently used letters stay towards the front of the list; if use of letters exhibits local correlations, this will result in a large number of small numbers such as "0"'s and "1"'s in the output.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] However, not all data exhibits this type of local correlation, and for some messages, the MTF transform may actually increase the entropy.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] An important use of the MTF transform is in Burrows–Wheeler transform based compression.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] The Burrows–Wheeler transform is very good at producing a sequence that exhibits local frequency correlation from text and certain other special classes of data.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] Compression benefits greatly from following up the Burrows–Wheeler transform with an MTF transform before the final entropy-encoding step.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] As an example, imagine we wish to compress Hamlet's soliloquy (*To be, or not to be...*).
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] We can calculate the size of this message to be 7033 bits.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] Naively, we might try to apply the MTF transform directly.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] The result is a message with 7807 bits (higher than the original).
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] The reason is that English text does not in general exhibit a high level of local frequency correlation.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] However, if we first apply the Burrows–Wheeler transform, and then the MTF transform, we get a message with 6187 bits.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] Note that the Burrows–Wheeler transform does not decrease the entropy of the message; it only reorders the bytes in a way that makes the MTF transform more effective.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] One problem with the basic MTF transform is that it makes the same changes for any character, regardless of frequency, which can result in diminished compression as characters that occur rarely may push frequent characters to higher values.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] Various alterations and alternatives have been developed for this reason.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] One common change is to make it so that characters above a certain point can only be moved to a certain threshold.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] Another is to make some algorithm that runs a count of each character's local frequency and uses these values to choose the characters' order at any point.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/move-to-front-transform] Many of these transforms still reserve zero for repeat characters, since these are often the most common in data after the Burrows–Wheeler Transform.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/run-length-encoding] Run-length encoding is most efficient on data that contains many such runs, for example, simple graphic images such as icons, line drawings, games, and animations.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/run-length-encoding] For files that do not have many runs, encoding them with RLE could increase the file size.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/run-length-encoding] RLE may also refer to particular image formats that use the encoding.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/run-length-encoding] RLE is an early graphics file format supported by CompuServe for compressing black and white images, that was widely supplanted by their later Graphics Interchange Format (GIF).
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/run-length-encoding] It is also the name of a little-used image format in Windows 3.x that is saved with the file extension `rle`, consisting of a run-length encoded bitmap; it was used as the format for the Windows 3.x startup screen.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/run-length-encoding] Run-length encoding (RLE) schemes were employed in the transmission of analog television signals as far back as 1967.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/run-length-encoding] In 1983, run-length encoding was patented by Hitachi.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/run-length-encoding] RLE is particularly well suited to palette-based bitmap images (which use relatively few colors) such as computer icons, and was a popular image compression method on early online services such as CompuServe before the advent of more sophisticated formats such as GIF.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/run-length-encoding] It does not work well on continuous-tone images (which use very many colors) such as photographs, although JPEG uses it on the coefficients that remain after transforming and quantizing image blocks.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/run-length-encoding] Common formats for run-length encoded data include Truevision TGA, PackBits (by Apple, used in MacPaint), PCX and ILBM.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/run-length-encoding] The International Telecommunication Union also describes a standard to encode run-length color for fax machines, known as T.45.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/run-length-encoding] That fax color coding standard, which along with other techniques is incorporated into Modified Huffman coding, is relatively efficient because most faxed documents are primarily white space, with occasional interruptions of black.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/run-length-encoding] RLE has a space complexity of ⁠ $O(n)$ ⁠, where n is the size of the input data.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/run-length-encoding] Run-length encoding compresses data by reducing the physical size of a repeating string of characters.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/run-length-encoding] This process involves converting the input data into a compressed format by identifying and counting consecutive occurrences of each character.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/run-length-encoding] Count the number of consecutive repeating characters (run length).
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/run-length-encoding] The decoding process involves reconstructing the original data from the encoded format by repeating characters according to their counts.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/run-length-encoding] For each count-character pair, repeat the character count times.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/run-length-encoding] Append these characters to the result string.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/run-length-encoding] Consider a screen containing plain black text on a solid white background.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/run-length-encoding] There will be many long runs of white pixels in the blank space, and many short runs of black pixels within the text.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/run-length-encoding] This can be interpreted as a sequence of twelve Ws, one B, twelve Ws, three Bs, etc., and represents the original 67 characters in only 18.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/run-length-encoding] While the actual format used for the storage of images is generally binary rather than ASCII characters like this, the principle remains the same.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/run-length-encoding] Even binary data files can be compressed with this method; file format specifications often dictate repeated bytes in files as padding space.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/run-length-encoding] However, newer compression methods such as DEFLATE often use LZ77-based algorithms, a generalization of run-length encoding that can take advantage of runs of strings of characters (such as `BWWBWWBWWBWW`).
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/run-length-encoding] Run-length encoding can be expressed in multiple ways to accommodate data properties as well as additional compression algorithms.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/run-length-encoding] For instance, one popular method encodes run lengths for runs of two or more characters only, using an "escape" symbol to identify runs, or using the character itself as the escape, so that any time a character appears twice it denotes a run.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/run-length-encoding] This would be interpreted as a run of twelve Ws, a B, a run of twelve Ws, a run of three Bs, etc.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/run-length-encoding] In data where runs are less frequent, this can significantly improve the compression rate.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/run-length-encoding] One other matter is the application of additional compression algorithms.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/run-length-encoding] To overcome this, some run-length encoders separate the data and escape symbols from the run lengths, so that the two can be handled independently.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/run-length-encoding] For the example data, this would result in two outputs, the string "`WWBWWBBWWBWW`" and the numbers (`12,12,3,24,14`).
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] In computer science, a **suffix array** is a sorted array of all suffixes of a string.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] It is a data structure used in, among others, full-text indices, data-compression algorithms, and the field of bibliometrics.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] Suffix arrays were introduced by Manber & Myers (1990) as a simple, space efficient alternative to suffix trees.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] They had independently been discovered by Gaston Gonnet in 1987 under the name *PAT array* (Gonnet, Baeza-Yates & Snider 1992).
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] Li, Li & Huo (2016) gave the first in-place ${\mathcal {O}}(n)$ time suffix array construction algorithm that is optimal both in time and space, where *in-place* means that the algorithm only needs ${\mathcal {O}}(1)$ additional space beyond the input string and the output suffix array.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] Enhanced suffix arrays (ESAs) are suffix arrays with additional tables that reproduce the full functionality of suffix trees preserving the same time and memory complexity.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] A sorted array of only some (rather than all) suffixes of a string is called a sparse suffix array.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] Let $S=S[1]S[2]...S[n]$ be an ${\textstyle n}$ -string and let $S[i,j]$ denote the substring of S ranging from i to j inclusive.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] The suffix array A of S is now defined to be an array of integers providing the starting positions of suffixes of S in lexicographical order.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] This means, an entry $A[i]$ contains the starting position of the i -th smallest suffix in S and thus for all $1\leq i\leq n$ : $S[A[i-1],n]<S[A[i],n]$ .
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] Each suffix of S shows up in A exactly once.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] These strings are sorted (as in a paper dictionary), before their starting positions (integer indices) are saved in A .
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] The text ends with the special sentinel letter `$` that is unique and lexicographically smaller than any other character.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] So for example, $A[3]$ contains the value 4, and therefore refers to the suffix starting at position 4 within S , which is the suffix `ana$`.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] It has been shown that every suffix tree algorithm can be systematically replaced with an algorithm that uses a suffix array enhanced with additional information (such as the LCP array) and solves the same problem in the same time complexity.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] Advantages of suffix arrays over suffix trees include improved space requirements, simpler linear time construction algorithms (e.g., compared to Ukkonen's algorithm) and improved cache locality.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] Suffix arrays were introduced by Manber & Myers (1990) in order to improve over the space requirements of suffix trees: Suffix arrays store n integers.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] Assuming an integer requires 4 bytes, a suffix array requires $4n$ bytes in total.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] This is significantly less than the $20n$ bytes which are required by a careful suffix tree implementation.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] However, in certain applications, the space requirements of suffix arrays may still be prohibitive.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] Analyzed in bits, a suffix array requires ${\mathcal {O}}(n\log n)$ space, whereas the original text over an alphabet of size $\sigma$ only requires ${\mathcal {O}}(n\log \sigma )$ bits.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] For a human genome with $\sigma =4$ and $n=3.4\times 10^{9}$ the suffix array would therefore occupy about 16 times more memory than the genome itself.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] Such discrepancies motivated a trend towards compressed suffix arrays and BWT-based compressed full-text indices such as the FM-index.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] These data structures require only space within the size of the text or even less.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] A suffix tree can be built in ${\mathcal {O}}(n)$ and can be converted into a suffix array by traversing the tree depth-first also in ${\mathcal {O}}(n)$ , so there exist algorithms that can build a suffix array in ${\mathcal {O}}(n)$ .
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] A naive approach to construct a suffix array is to use a comparison-based sorting algorithm.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] These algorithms require ${\mathcal {O}}(n\log n)$ suffix comparisons, but a suffix comparison runs in ${\mathcal {O}}(n)$ time, so the overall runtime of this approach is ${\mathcal {O}}(n^{2}\log n)$ .
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] More advanced algorithms take advantage of the fact that the suffixes to be sorted are not arbitrary strings but related to each other.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] One of the first algorithms to achieve all goals is the SA-IS algorithm of Nong, Zhang & Chan (2009).
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] The algorithm is also rather simple (< 100 LOC) and can be enhanced to simultaneously construct the LCP array.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] The SA-IS algorithm is one of the fastest known suffix array construction algorithms.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] A careful implementation by Yuta Mori outperforms most other linear or super-linear construction approaches.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] A well-known recursive algorithm for integer alphabets is the *DC3 / skew* algorithm of Kärkkäinen & Sanders (2003).
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] It runs in linear time and has successfully been used as the basis for parallel and external memory suffix array construction algorithms.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] (2010) proposes an algorithm for updating the suffix array of a text that has been edited instead of rebuilding a new suffix array from scratch.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] In practical open source work, a commonly used routine for suffix array construction was qsufsort, based on the 1999 Larsson-Sadakane algorithm.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] This routine has been superseded by Yuta Mori's DivSufSort, "the fastest known suffix sorting algorithm in main memory" as of 2017.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] It too can be modified to compute an LCP array.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] It uses a induced copying combined with Itoh-Tanaka.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] In 2021 a faster implementation of the algorithm was presented by Ilya Grebnov which in average showed 65% performance improvement over DivSufSort implementation on the Silesia corpus.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] The concept of a suffix array can be extended to more than one string.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] This is called a generalized suffix array (or GSA), a suffix array that contains all suffixes for a set of strings (for example, $S=S_{1},S_{2},S_{3},...,S_{k}$ and is lexicographically sorted with all suffixes of each string.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] The suffix array of a string can be used as an index to quickly locate every occurrence of a substring pattern P within the string S .
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] Finding every occurrence of the pattern is equivalent to finding every suffix that begins with the substring.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] Thanks to the lexicographical ordering, these suffixes will be grouped together in the suffix array and can be found efficiently with two binary searches.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] Finding the substring pattern P of length m in the string S of length n takes ${\mathcal {O}}(m\log n)$ time, given that a single suffix comparison needs to compare m characters.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] Manber & Myers (1990) describe how this bound can be improved to ${\mathcal {O}}(m+\log n)$ time using LCP information.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] The idea is that a pattern comparison does not need to re-compare certain characters, when it is already known that these are part of the longest common prefix of the pattern and the current search interval.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] Abouelhoda, Kurtz & Ohlebusch (2004) improve the bound even further and achieve a search time of ${\mathcal {O}}(m)$ for constant alphabet size, as known from suffix trees.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] Suffix sorting algorithms can be used to compute the Burrows–Wheeler transform (BWT).
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] The BWT requires sorting of all cyclic permutations of a string.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] If this string ends in a special end-of-string character that is lexicographically smaller than all other character (i.e., $), then the order of the sorted rotated BWT matrix corresponds to the order of suffixes in a suffix array.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] The BWT can therefore be computed in linear time by first constructing a suffix array of the text and then deducing the BWT string: $BWT[i]=S[A[i]-1]$ .
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] Suffix arrays can also be used to look up substrings in example-based machine translation, demanding much less storage than a full phrase table as used in Statistical machine translation.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] Many additional applications of the suffix array require the LCP array.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] Some of these are detailed in the application section of the latter.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] Suffix trees are powerful data structures that have wide application in areas of pattern and string matching, indexing and textual statistics.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] However, it occupies a significant amount of space and thus has a drawback in many real-time applications that require processing a considerably large amount of data like genome analysis.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] To overcome this drawback, the Enhanced Suffix Array was developed.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] It is a data structure consisting of a suffix array and an additional table called the child table that contains the information about the parent-child relationship between the nodes in the suffix tree.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] The node branching data structure for this tree is a linked list.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] Enhanced suffix arrays are superior to suffix trees in terms of both space efficiency and time complexity and are easy to implement.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] Moreover, they can be applied to any algorithm that uses a suffix tree by using an abstract concept called LCP-interval trees.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] The time complexity for searching a pattern of length m in an enhanced suffix array is ${\mathcal {O}}(m|\Sigma |)$ .
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] 2. lcp array lcp[1,...n]: It is an array of n integers that maintains the lengths of the longest common prefix of two consecutive suffixes stored in the pos array.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] The length of the longest common prefix of pos[i − 1] and pos[i] is stored in lcp[i],where 2 ≤ i ≤ n.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] The lcp-interval portrays the same parent-child relationship as that among the associated nodes in the suffix tree of S.This shows that if the corresponding node of [i..j] is a child of the corresponding node of [k..l], a lcp-interval [i..j] is a child interval of another lcp-interval [k..l].
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] If [k..l] is a child interval of [i..j], a lcp-interval [i..j] is the parent interval of a lcp-interval [k..l].
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] The child table *cldtab* is composed of three n arrays, *up*, *down* and *nextlIndex*.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] The information about the edges of the corresponding suffix tree is stored and maintained by the *up* and *down* arrays.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] The *nextlIndex* array stores the links in the linked list used for node branching the suffix tree.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] The initial index of the second child interval of the longest lcp-interval, starting at index *i* is stored in the element *down[i]*.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] If and only if the interval is neither the first child nor the final child of its parent, the element *nextlIndex[i]* contains the first index of the next sibling interval of the longest lcp-interval, starting at index *i*.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] By performing a bottom-up traversal of the lcp-interval of the tree, the child table can be constructed in linear time.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] The *up/down* values and the *nextlIndex* values can be computed separately by using two distinct algorithms.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] The suffix links for an enhanced suffix array can be computed by generating the suffix link interval [*1,..,r*] for each [i,..j] interval during the preprocessing.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] The left and right elements l and r of the interval are maintained in the first index of [i,..,j].
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] The table for this interval ranges from 0 to n.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] The suffix link table is constructed by the left-to-right breadth-first traversal of the lcp-interval tree.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] Every time an *l*-interval is computed, it is added to the list of l-intervals, which is referred to as the l-list.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] When the lcp-value > 0, for every *l*-interval[i,..,j] in the list, link[i] is calculated.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] The interval [*l*,..,*r*] is computed by a binary search in(*l*-1)-list, where *l* is the largest left boundary amongst all the *l*-1 intervals.
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] The suffix link interval of [i,..j] is represented by this interval[*l,..,r*].
[src:burrows-wheeler-bwt/suffix-array] The values *l* and *r* are ultimately stored in the first index of [i,..,j].
